	url = {https://advances.sciencemag.org/content/5/4/eaav5532},
	doi = {10.1126/sciadv.aav5532},
	abstract = {A long-term goal for superconductors is to increase the superconducting transition temperature, TC. In cuprates, TC depends strongly on the out-of-plane Cu-apical oxygen distance and the in-plane Cu-O distance, but there has been little attention paid to tuning them independently. Here, in simply grown, self-assembled, vertically aligned nanocomposite thin films of La2CuO4+δ + LaCuO3, by strongly increasing out-of-plane distances without reducing in-plane distances (three-dimensional strain engineering), we achieve superconductivity up to 50 K in the vertical interface regions, spaced {\textasciitilde}50 nm apart. No additional process to supply excess oxygen, e.g., by ozone or high-pressure oxygen annealing, was required, as is normally the case for plain La2CuO4+δ films. Our proof-of-concept work represents an entirely new approach to increasing TC in cuprates or other superconductors.
We demonstrate a new way to increase the superconducting TC of cuprates using 3-D strain control in nanocomposite thin films.
We demonstrate a new way to increase the superconducting TC of cuprates using 3-D strain control in nanocomposite thin films.},
